Problem Statement¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective¶

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customers age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Observations on Age¶

Based on the histogram and boxplot for the "Age" variable, here are a few observations:

Distribution Shape: The histogram indicates that the age distribution is fairly uniform with a slight concentration around the median age. There doesn't appear to be any significant skewness to the left or right, suggesting a relatively even distribution of customers across different ages.

Central Tendency: The boxplot above the histogram shows that the median age (indicated by the line inside the box) is roughly in the mid-40s, which corresponds to the peak in the histogram.

Variability: The boxplot's interquartile range (the width of the box) suggests that the middle 50% of customers' ages are spread across a decent range, likely around 20 years or so, indicating a good mix of ages among the bank's customers.

Outliers: There do not appear to be any outliers on either end of the age spectrum, as there are no points plotted beyond the "whiskers" of the boxplot.

Symmetry: The symmetry of the boxplot, along with the relatively flat histogram, suggests that the age data is quite symmetric around the median.

Potential Issues: There do not appear to be any immediate issues with the "Age" data that would require cleanup, such as outliers or missing values.

This well-distributed age data is good for analysis, as it indicates a diverse customer base in terms of age, which can be beneficial when trying to generalize findings or build predictive models.

Outliers: There are many outliers on the higher end, indicating that a smaller number of customers have very high mortgage values. These are beyond the upper whisker of the boxplot.

Low Mortgage Customers: The vast majority of customers either do not have a mortgage or have a very small mortgage value on their house, which could be indicative of the customer base's financial behaviors or the bank's mortgage product uptake.

Analytical Considerations: Given the large number of zero values, any predictive models would need to handle this distribution appropriately, possibly treating the presence of a mortgage as a separate binary feature and the amount as a conditional feature only for those with a mortgage.

Financial Product Opportunities: The data suggests there could be an opportunity to market mortgage products to customers who currently do not have a mortgage, considering the large proportion of such customers.

The prevalence of zero or low mortgage values might indicate that mortgages are not as commonly held among the customers of the bank, or that the dataset includes a significant number of younger or less financially leveraged individuals.

In [ ]:
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()
In [ ]:
### function to plot distributions wrt target


def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

Model Building¶

First, let's create functions to calculate different metrics and confusion matrix so that we don't have to use the same code repeatedly for each model.

  • The model_performance_classification_sklearn function will be used to check the model performance of models.
  • The confusion_matrix_sklearnfunction will be used to plot confusion matrix.
In [ ]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [ ]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Data for feature importance
features = ['Income', 'Family', 'Education_2', 'Education_3', 'CCAvg']
importance = [0.297816, 0.248530, 0.165238, 0.144207, 0.047550]

# Create bar graph
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
bars = plt.bar(features, importance, color='skyblue')
plt.ylabel('Importance')
plt.title('Feature Importance for the Base Decision Tree Model')

# Add the importance values on top of the bars
for bar in bars:
    yval = bar.get_height()
    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, yval, round(yval, 4), ha='center', va='bottom')

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Pre-Pruning¶

# Choose the type of classifier.
estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {
    "max_depth": np.arange(6, 15),
    "min_samples_leaf": [1, 2, 5, 7, 10],
    "max_leaf_nodes": [2, 3, 5, 10],
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
acc_scorer = make_scorer(recall_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(estimator, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer, cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
estimator = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
estimator.fit(X_train, y_train) ## Complete the code to fit model on train data

Observations¶

Training Set Results: Confusion Matrix:

True Negatives: 3,168 False Positives: 1 False Negatives: 42 True Positives: 289 Performance Metrics:

Accuracy: 98.77% Recall: 87.31% Precision: 99.66% F1 Score: 93.08% The training set results indicate a high level of accuracy, precision, and F1 score. The model has almost perfect precision, which suggests it rarely makes a mistake when it predicts that someone will take a loan. However, there are more false negatives than false positives, meaning that the model misses some individuals who would take a loan (lower recall).

Testing Set Results: Confusion Matrix:

True Negatives: 1,351 False Positives: 0 False Negatives: 32 True Positives: 117 Performance Metrics:

Accuracy: 97.87% Recall: 78.52% Precision: 100% F1 Score: 87.97% The testing set results also show a high level of accuracy and an even higher precision than the training set, reaching a perfect score. However, recall has dropped, which means the model misses more actual loan takers when applied to the test set.

Comparison and Insights: Accuracy: Both training and testing results are very high, which is good but should be taken with caution due to the class imbalance in the data.

Recall: The model has a higher recall on the training set than on the test set. This suggests that the model might be slightly overfitting to the training data, capturing the nuances of the training set that don't generalize as well to the test set.

Precision: The model has very high precision on both sets, with a perfect precision score on the test set. This indicates that when the model predicts a customer will take a loan, it is almost always right.

F1 Score: The F1 score is high for both sets, which suggests a good balance between recall and precision. However, the slight drop in the F1 score on the test set compared to the training set could also indicate some overfitting.

Overfitting: The fact that the recall and F1 score are slightly lower on the test set might suggest that the model is overfitting to the training data, despite the precision remaining very high. It's managing to capture most of the nuances of the training set but is missing some of those in the test set.

Generalization: Despite the potential for overfitting, the model's performance on the test set is still very strong, suggesting it has learned generalizable patterns.

Business Implication: Given the objective of predicting personal loan uptake, the model's tendency to predict fewer false positives (at the cost of higher false negatives) could be acceptable depending on the cost associated with each type of error. If the cost of a false positive (offering a loan to someone who won't accept it) is high, this model would be beneficial. However, if the goal is to not miss any potential loan customers, the recall should be improved.

In conclusion, the model is performing well in terms of the metrics considered. But depending on the specific cost-benefit analysis (i.e., the cost of false positives versus false negatives), you may want to adjust the decision threshold to capture more true positives if increasing recall is a priority. Further investigation into the ROC curve and Precision-Recall curve could provide additional insights to refine the model's performance.

Observations¶

Heres a summary based on the plots and the data:

Total Impurity vs. Effective Alpha for Training Set: This plot shows how the total impurity of the leaves of the decision tree increases with higher values of ccp_alpha. Initially, as ccp_alpha increases, there is a slow increase in total impurity, indicating the model is getting rid of complexity without sacrificing much accuracy. However, there is a significant jump in impurity at higher alpha values, which suggests over-pruning.

Number of Nodes vs. Alpha: The plot shows a sharp decrease in the number of nodes as ccp_alpha increases at first, with the number stabilizing after a certain point. This suggests that most of the tree's complexity is reduced early in the pruning process.

Depth vs. Alpha: Similar to the number of nodes, the depth of the tree decreases rapidly with an increase in ccp_alpha initially and then flattens out, indicating that a less complex tree is achieved without drastically increasing alpha.

Recall vs. Alpha for Training and Testing Sets: The recall remains fairly stable across a range of ccp_alpha values before it starts to drop, first for the test set and then for the training set. This indicates that up to a certain point, pruning does not negatively affect the model's ability to correctly identify the positive class. However, beyond a certain ccp_alpha threshold, the model's sensitivity decreases.

Table of Output for Cost Complexity Pruning: The table lists the ccp_alpha values alongside the corresponding total impurities. It looks like the impurity begins to rise more steeply at the later alpha values, which correspond to the points where the recall drops significantly in the Recall vs. Alpha plot.

The key takeaway from these observations is that there is a range of ccp_alpha values that effectively simplify the tree without a significant loss in recall. Choosing a ccp_alpha value within this range would give a pruned tree that balances complexity and performance well.

plt.title('Feature Importance for the Post Pruned Decision Tree Model')

# Add the importance values on top of the bars

    yval = bar.get_height()
    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, yval, round(yval, 4), ha='center', va='bottom')

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

What recommedations would you suggest to the bank?

Based on the analysis and the objective to predict the likelihood of a liability customer purchasing a personal loan, here are some key pieces of advice for the bank:

Model Selection:

Choose the decision tree model that balances recall and precision according to the bank's strategy. If avoiding false negatives is critical (ensuring that potential loan customers are not missed), prioritize recall. If the bank wants to minimize the cost of targeting unlikely customers, prioritize precision. Model Performance:

Monitor the performance of the model closely after deployment, as the real-world effectiveness in identifying loan customers might differ from the test performance. Regularly update the model with new data to ensure it remains relevant and accurate over time. Customer Segmentation:

Use the model to identify characteristics of customers who are more likely to purchase a loan. These might include income level, credit card usage, and other key attributes identified by the model as significant predictors. Target marketing efforts more strategically by focusing on customer segments most likely to convert, as indicated by the model's findings. Risk Management:

Understand the trade-offs between a conservative approach (high precision, low recall) and a more aggressive approach (lower precision, higher recall). Choose an approach that aligns with the banks risk appetite and business strategy. Product Offers:

Tailor personal loan offers to individual customers based on the model's insights. For instance, customers with higher income might be offered larger loans, whereas those with higher credit card spending might be offered loans with promotional rates. Model Interpretability:

Given that decision trees are inherently interpretable, use the model's transparency to gain buy-in from stakeholders. Explain how the model makes predictions and which factors are most influential. Compliance and Ethics:

Ensure that the model's use complies with all regulatory requirements, especially concerning fair lending practices. Regularly audit the model for any biases or ethical concerns, particularly if using demographic variables like age, family size, etc. Continuous Learning:

Set up a feedback loop to learn which customers accepted the loan offers and refine the model accordingly. This could involve A/B testing of different strategies or more nuanced customer segmentation. Cross-Selling Strategy:

Incorporate insights from the model into broader cross-selling initiatives. For example, customers who are identified as likely to take a loan might also be interested in other financial products. Customer Engagement:

Engage with customers predicted to be on the fence about taking a loan with personalized communication and education about the benefits of the banks loan products. In summary, the bank should use the insights gained from the model to inform a customer-centric marketing strategy that not only focuses on those most likely to convert but also respects the customer's needs and preferences, all while ensuring ethical and compliant use of the model.

Model Selection: Pre-Pruned Model: This model showed a balance with high precision but slightly lower recall compared to the post-pruned model. It seems to be more conservative in predicting loan takers.

Post-Pruned Model: The performance metrics of this model on the testing data replicated the base model's metrics, indicating that it does not overfit and maintains good generalization without compromising too much on recall.

Recommendation: Given the need to maximize the detection of potential loan customers without significantly increasing the risk of reaching out inappropriately (high false positives), the post-pruned model might be more suitable. This model provides a balanced approach with a robust recall rate and excellent precision, ensuring that the bank effectively identifies potential loan customers while maintaining a quality interaction with less likelihood of misclassification.

In summary, the bank should prioritize a model that ensures high recall to avoid missing out on potential loan customers but still maintains a good level of precision to keep the campaign's relevance and effectiveness. The post-pruned model aligns well with these requirements, supporting the bank's strategic goals of expanding its loan customer base and improving the efficiency of its marketing campaigns.
